00:00:48.444 --> 00:00:49.860
JEN TONG: So the
way they discover

00:00:49.860 --> 00:00:53.670
planets around other stars is
by combining their efforts using

00:00:53.670 --> 00:00:54.730
the cloud.

00:00:54.730 --> 00:00:56.970
So what happens is, each
night, the telescopes

00:00:56.970 --> 00:00:59.970
will all wake up
and look at the sky.

00:00:59.970 --> 00:01:02.850
And they'll get a bunch of
great images of the sky.

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:04.560
And then, when the
day comes, they'll

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:06.240
go to sleep but not really.

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:08.730
They're going to start uploading
all their data to Cloud

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:10.080
Platform.

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:13.330
And from there, we can
combine all the data together,

00:01:13.330 --> 00:01:15.030
aggregate it, and
then, from that,

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:18.507
we can infer the existence of
planets around other stars.

00:01:18.507 --> 00:01:21.090
TODD KERPELMAN: And how do you
infer the existence of planets?

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:23.580
JEN TONG: So planets are
very hard to see directly,

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:25.180
because their stars
are very bright,

00:01:25.180 --> 00:01:28.180
and there's lots of glare,
and they're very far away.

00:01:28.180 --> 00:01:32.370
In fact, a star only looks
like one pixel on the camera.

00:01:32.370 --> 00:01:34.540
So we have to use some
trickery to do that.

00:01:34.540 --> 00:01:37.320
So instead of looking
for the planet directly,

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:40.920
we look for a
dimming of the star

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:43.050
when the planet moves
between us and the star,

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:44.190
kind of like an eclipse.

00:01:44.190 --> 00:01:46.795
Or we call it a transit
in the more general case.

00:01:46.795 --> 00:01:48.420
TODD KERPELMAN: And
so the general idea

00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:50.520
is you've got hundreds
of telescopes, all

00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:52.740
around the world, taking
pictures of the night sky.

00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:55.740
They combine all those images
up to Google Cloud, which

00:01:55.740 --> 00:01:57.720
analyzes them all and
looks for a star that

00:01:57.720 --> 00:01:59.699
dims on a regular
enough basis that you

00:01:59.699 --> 00:02:01.740
think it must be because
there's a planet passing

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:02.610
in front of it.

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:03.750
JEN TONG: That is
exactly correct.

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:05.520
So we're able to infer
that just by having

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:07.811
a whole bunch of samples from
having a very large fleet

00:02:07.811 --> 00:02:08.699
of telescopes.

00:02:08.699 --> 00:02:10.630
TODD KERPELMAN: Wow,
that's very interesting.

00:02:10.630 --> 00:02:12.930
Now, if I remember from
being three years old,

00:02:12.930 --> 00:02:14.430
