00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:17.010
How can you tell that a
star is dimming because

00:02:17.010 --> 00:02:20.420
of a planet passing in front
of it versus normal star

00:02:20.420 --> 00:02:21.210
twinkling?

00:02:21.210 --> 00:02:24.034
Which is totally
a technical term.

00:02:24.034 --> 00:02:25.200
JEN TONG: Totally technical.

00:02:25.200 --> 00:02:27.380
And that's a great
question, because that's

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:30.240
part of the stuff that
makes PANOPTES special.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:33.660
Because we're using commercial,
off-the-shelf cameras instead

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:35.814
of specialized
astronomy sensors,

00:02:35.814 --> 00:02:37.230
we have to compensate
for the fact

00:02:37.230 --> 00:02:39.630
that those cameras are
designed to take color photos.

00:02:39.630 --> 00:02:41.700
Because when a camera
takes color photos,

00:02:41.700 --> 00:02:43.890
it filters some of the
light out using a thing

00:02:43.890 --> 00:02:45.250
called a Bayer filter.

00:02:45.250 --> 00:02:48.272
And when the star twinkles, it
moves around that Bayer filter.

00:02:48.272 --> 00:02:50.730
And it makes it much harder to
count the number of photons.

00:02:50.730 --> 00:02:52.480
Because we don't know
how much are getting

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:54.026
filtered out by
the Bayer filter.

00:02:54.026 --> 00:02:55.650
So the way we compensate
for that is we

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:57.810
look for another star,
in the same picture,

00:02:57.810 --> 00:03:00.630
that has the exact
same amount of twinkle.

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:03.807
And from that, we can
do a relative brightness

00:03:03.807 --> 00:03:06.390
measurement, because we know how
bright those stars should be,

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:08.100
because we can
identify the star.

00:03:08.100 --> 00:03:11.089
And that's how we kind of
cancel out the twinkle.

